1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
3 HOUSE
RESOLUTION 1053 By: Gann
4
5
6
7 AS INTRODUCED
8 A Resolution expressing formal opposition to the
proposed Inola Aluminum Smelter project; directing
9 distribution.
10
11
12 WHEREAS, The proposed Inola aluminum smelter would constitute
13 one of the largest industrial developments ever proposed in this
14 region and is expected to create significant long-term impacts on
15 Oklahoma and neighboring states; and
16 WHEREAS, This project raises substantial concerns regarding
17 potential emissions of fluorides, particulate matter, sulfur
18 dioxide, nitrogen oxides, and other smelting-related byproducts that
19 may affect public health, property use, agriculture, and quality of
20 life; and
21 WHEREAS, Local government has a duty to exercise caution before
22 supporting any project that may create long-term burdens on roads,
23 bridges, fire protection, emergency medical response, land use,
24 agriculture, water resources, and residential growth patterns.
Req. No. 17519

1 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
2 OF THE 2ND SESSION OF THE 60TH OKLAHOMA LEGISLATURE:
3 THAT the Oklahoma House of Representatives formally declares its
4 opposition to advancement of the proposed Inola aluminum smelter
5 project unless and until all environmental, agricultural,
6 infrastructure, public-safety, and fiscal concerns are independently
7 studied and publicly addressed to the satisfaction of affected local
8 communities.
9 THAT the Oklahoma House of Representatives further recommends
10 that no public support be endorsed unless all participating public
11 entities provide a complete public accounting of all incentives,
12 abatements, grants, TIF districts, state and federal subsidies, and
13 utility subsidies, associated with the project.
14 THAT copies of this resolution be distributed to the Governor
15 and the Oklahoma Department of Environmental Quality.
